\begin_layout Section
Data types
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are different kinds of data needed for different features in Gitools.
 Here we explain them independently on how can they be represented in the
 file system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A matrix is a bidimensional structure in which for each dimension (row and
 column) there is a value (cell).
 All the values are of the same type (for example all are p-values or log
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

ratios).
 For R users it is the equivalent to 
\emph on
matrix
\emph default
.
 Matrices can contain continuous values (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

) or binary values (1, 0).
 There could be empty values too (usually represented as a hyphen '-' in
 text file formats).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Matrices provide values for a number of items (i.e.
 one gene for each row) in several conditions (i.e.
 one condition for each column).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Modules are lists of genes or other biological elements with a common biological
 property.
 They are also known as gene sets or concepts.
 For example, genes in the same pathway or genes regulated by the same transcrip
tion factor form a module.
 You can have many modules, i.e one for each known pathway or TF as seen
 in the example before.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A table represents a list of attributes, where each row is an element of
 the list and each column an attribute.
 Each attribute can be of different type (i.e.
 one column with the gene id and other with a log
\begin_inset Formula $_{2}$
\end_inset

ratio).
 For R users it is the equivalent to 
\emph on
data.frame
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Gitools they are used for different things, for providing extra attributes
 to row and column labels in heatmaps and for representing results of some
 analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
File formats
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data can be retrieved from or stored in files in many different formats.
 Some file formats are useful to represent different kind of data, too.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any of the presented formats can be compressed using 
\emph on
gzip
\emph default
 and recognized if the suffix 
\emph on
.gz
\emph default
 is appended at the end of the file name, so for example the file matrix.cdm
 could be compressed using 
\emph on
gzip
\emph default
 and renamed to matrix.cdm.gz and Gitools would be able to read it without
 problems.
\end_layout

