\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Binary data matrix (BDM)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
BDM file format is a tab delimited binary matrix of items (i.e.
 genes) and conditions.
 Values can only be 1 or 0, and can have different meanings depending what
 are they used for.
 Empty values can be represented with the hyphen '-'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They are useful for representing matrices as well as modules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When representing matrices a 1 means that this item (row) presents a positive
 event (for example a mutation) in this condition (column) and 0 otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When representing modules, rows correspond to genes or biological elements
 and each column a different module, then a 1 is used to specify that a
 given gene or biological element is related to a given module and 0 otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename images/format_BDM.png
	lyxscale 20

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gene matrix transposed (GMT)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
GMT file format is a simple tab delimited file to provide gene sets.
 Each row describes a gene set, the first column indicates the name of the
 gene set and the second column the description (you can leave description
 empty), the rest of columns are used to enumerate the genes related to
 this gene set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually this format is used for representing modules but can also be used
 to represent binary data matrices (i.e.
 when you have lists of differentially expressed gens for different conditions).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
